{"plugins":{"posthtml-include":{"root":"./src"},"posthtml-expressions":{"root":"./src/partials","locals":{"top":[{"type":"text","value":"In the wake of the COVID-19 coronavirus pandemic, university administrators and government officials across the world acted to curb the effects of the virus on student populations, evacuating thousands of students from campus and shifting to online courses in a matter of weeks."},{"type":"graphic","value":{"asset":"lede.html","steps":["On March 10, seven days after the United States reported its first hundred cases, Harvard, Cornell, and Yale became the first Ivies to respond to the coronavirus outbreak by announcing mandatory move-out for students.","Columbia was the last Ivy to announce mandatory move-out, five days after the first Ivies.","In that five day time span, the number of national cases had almost quadrupled.","On average, the Ivy League universities took 8.375 days to respond after the first hundred reported cases in the nation.","This response rate equaled that of <c>China</c>, the first country to begin experiencing an outbreak in late January. 5 days after the first hundred reported cases, when the national number of cases had reached 2,863, the government mandated the closure of all schools.","The Ivies’ responses were far slower than that of <c>South Korea</c>, which began experiencing an outbreak in late February. The South Korean government closed schools across the country 2 days after the first hundred reported cases.","The number of national cases at the time of Columbia’s response matches that of Italy, which has faced significant criticism for its delays. Italy began experiencing an outbreak in early March.","They responded by closing schools when there were 3,858 cases, <t>11 days after</t> the first hundred reported cases.","The United States began experiencing an outbreak in mid-March, long after effects had been seen in China, South Korea, and Italy. The lack of coordinated national response led to delays in school closures, discrepancies in state recommendations, and lack of proactive efforts to inform university students of social distancing practices, according to experts.","The United States, now with XXX cases at the time of publication, has surpassed the rest of the world."]}}],"credits":"","footer":"<a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Hong-Sen-Du/\">Hong Sen Du</a> is a developer at Spectator. <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Jason-Kao\">Jason Kao</a> is a Graphics deputy editor. Additional reporting by <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Griffin-Jones\">Griffin Jones</a>.\n\nProduced with <a href=\"https://github.com/spec-journalism/spectate/\">Spectate</a> by the Spectator <a href=\"https://github.com/spec-journalism\">Graphics</a> team.","headline":"The U.S. and Ivy League schools were late to respond to COVID-19. Data shows international universities did better.","date":"April 13, 2020","byline":"By <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Kelly-Pu/\">Kelly Pu</a>, <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Jun-Yi-Zhang/\">Jun Yi Zhang</a>, <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Stephanie-Lai/\">Stephanie Lai</a>, <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Raeedah-Wahid/\">Raeedah Wahid</a>\nInteractives by <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Hong-Sen-Du/\">Hong Sen Du</a> and <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Jason-Kao/\">Jason Kao</a>\nEdited by <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Karen-Xia\">Karen Xia</a>","body":[{"type":"text","value":"Public health experts raised concerns over U.S. schools’ slow reactions to the COVID-19 pandemic, citing a lack of national and international coordination, widespread lack of preparation for the evolving virus by U.S. institutions, and miscommunication between the government and universities."},{"type":"text","value":"Trends from Ivy League schools revealed no uniform response, which public health experts said mirrored that of universities across the nation, attributing it to the lack of uniform national direction. In light of the pandemic, the Ivy League helped shape conversations among higher education institutions and their response rates highlighted the national trend. According to <a href=\"https://www.chronicle.com/interactives/covid-closures-part-2?cid=cp277\">the Chronicle</a>, on average, U.S. universities closed on March 12, four days after the Ivy League school average."},{"type":"graphic","value":{"asset":"columbia-graphic.html"}},{"type":"text","value":"Most universities reported a positive case among a college affiliate around the second week of March and thus reacted at a similar rate. Many Ivy League schools seemed to follow suit after Columbia’s initial response, yet Columbia was the last to force students to vacate campus."},{"type":"graphic","value":{"asset":"schools.html"}},{"type":"text","value":"According to public health experts, U.S. school administrators were prompted to take action by suspected or confirmed cases within their respective communities rather than taking precautionary measures. Consequently, their actions lagged behind those taken by their counterparts in other countries which saw the impact of COVID-19 prior to the United States."},{"type":"text","value":"Across the Ivies, Spectator found universities also responded to the first case in their state at differing rates, which experts said resulted from lack of federal guidance on handling the virus. Countries like China and Italy, on the other hand, had a unified response."},{"type":"text","value":"Bernadette Boden-Albala, the dean of Public Health at the University of California, Irvine, attributed the U.S. and many of its universities’ delayed responses to misinformation and the evolving understanding health experts had on the virus."},{"type":"text","value":"“Early countrywide public health decisions were delayed, and there are consequences to those early delays,” Boden-Albala said."},{"type":"text","value":"The delay in U.S. response may also be the result of lack of international communication and coordination, said School of International Affairs professor Robert Jervis."},{"type":"text","value":"“There’s been no attempt from us to lead international coordination [in] any way,” Jervis said, citing the country’s decision to cancel flights from Europe without consulting the countries impacted by the travel ban before the announcement."},{"type":"text","value":"While other countries took after China as a model of combatting the virus, the United States <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/11/us/politics/coronavirus-trump-response.html\">mostly waited</a> for the virus to escalate before taking reactionary measures due to the general misunderstanding of the scope of the virus, Boden-Albaba said. She noted that much of the U.S. public had seen China’s tactics as extreme."},{"type":"text","value":"“We were all surprised when China decided to lock down an entire province, it seemed almost inconceivable,” Jervis added."},{"type":"text","value":"Boden-Albala said many U.S. universities failed to take proactive measures to better inform students, including campaigns on how to prepare for the virus through handwashing and transmission prevention."},{"type":"text","value":"“Universities should have taken action earlier to make sure students were more informed to decrease viral spread—focusing on influenza if nothing else because the same practices are still the same one that would stop transmission of coronavirus,” she said."},{"type":"text","value":"While universities waited for public health officials to send them messages to shut down, administrators took additional measures to ensure students suspected to have come in contact with the virus self-quarantined, and they canceled events."},{"type":"text","value":"Columbia requested students not to gather in groups of 25 people on March 5, but still had not canceled classes, leaving faculty members unsure if their classes would still function."},{"type":"text","value":"For University students—who believed the virus had no effect on them—the messaging from administrators and the public left <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/news/2020/03/30/inconsistent-messaging-around-young-peoples-covid-19-risk-contributes-to-spread-of-infection/\">students misinformed</a> over the risks of the virus and preventative measures."},{"type":"text","value":"At the University of Pennsylvania, administrators sent out two different move-out dates, March 15 and 17 and moved commencement online but later changed their mind to postpone it. These actions may have contributed to the spread of misinformation on the impact of the virus to students."},{"type":"text","value":"Similar actions were taken at Columbia, Yale, Princeton, and Dartmouth. These universities originally only announced remote classes for a few weeks and later extended them to the entire semester in order to respond to the rapidly changing nature of the virus as recommended by government officials. At the time of the initial announcement, students may not have understood the severity of the situation until weeks later when they were forced to evacuate."},{"type":"text","value":"<b>Harvard</b><b> and Cornell</b> were the first Ivy League schools to announce a move to online instruction for the rest of the semester on March 10. Yale announced mandatory move-out on the same day."},{"type":"graphic","value":{"asset":"harvard.html"}},{"type":"text","value":"Cornell was the last Ivy to see positive cases within its community. It also set the latest move-out deadline of March 28."},{"type":"graphic","value":{"asset":"cornell.html"}},{"type":"text","value":"However, Dustin Duncan, a social and spatial epidemiologist at the Columbia Mailman School of Public Health, said he believes the University responded to the crisis in a clear and timely manner. Universities, he said, likely reacted based on recommendations from public health officials and epidemiologists to make administrative decisions."},{"type":"text","value":"“I think that it is and remains to be a rapidly changing landscape of what to do,” Duncan said. “And then comparing COVID to other [societies] ... I think that the issue of the emerging effects of this disease is we’re learning about the disease as it’s happening.”"},{"type":"text","value":"Arthur Reingold, an epidemiology professor at the University of California, Berkeley, said university administrators reacted based on the mixed messaging they received from federal agencies."},{"type":"text","value":"“Different levels of government provid[ed] different messages, the federal government, the White House, providing one message, federal health authorities and state health authorities a different message,” Reingold said. “I think that’s probably the biggest problem is that the messaging is not being consistent and many people are uncertain or confused about exactly what the right response is.”"},{"type":"text","value":"Despite these concerns, Bolden-Albala added that Columbia, as well as University of Washington and UCI ultimately responded in a timely manner, citing the presence of well-established public health schools, which led to conversations between high-level administrators and experts on how to prepare and address the crisis."},{"type":"text","value":"Still, she said she found the response rate and conflicting information alarming, citing those among the reasons for the rapid spread across the United States."},{"type":"text","value":"“We need to all work together now to keep some semblance of calm as we deal with the current grim reality,” Bolden-Albala said."},{"type":"text","value":"<i>Kelly Pu is a Graphics deputy editor at Spectator. She can be contacted at </i><a href=\"mailto:kelly.pu@columbiaspectator.com\"><i>kelly.pu@columbiaspectator.com</i></a>."},{"type":"text","value":"<i>Jun Yi Zhang is a Graphics reporter at Spectator. She can be contacted at </i><a href=\"mailto:junyi.zhang@columbiaspectator.com\"><i>junyi.zhang@columbiaspectator.com</i></a>."},{"type":"text","value":"<i>Stephanie Lai is a News editor at Spectator. She can be contacted at </i><a href=\"mailto:stephanie.lai@columbiaspectator.com\"><i>stephanie.lai@columbiaspectator.com</i></a><i>. Follow her on Twitter </i><a href=\"https://twitter.com/stephaniealai\"><i>@stephaniealai</i></a>."},{"type":"text","value":"<i>Raeedah Wahid is the Graphics editor at Spectator. She can be contacted at </i><a href=\"mailto:raeedah.wahid@columbiaspectator.com\"><i>raeedah.wahid@columbiaspectator.com</i></a><i>. Follow her on Twitter </i><a href=\"https://twitter.com/raeedahwahid\"><i>@raeedahwahid</i></a>."}],"methodology":"<b>About the numbers\n</b>\nData regarding the global number of coronavirus cases was compiled by the <a href=\"https://github.com/datasets/covid-19/tree/master/data\">Center for Systems Science and Engineering</a> at Johns Hopkins. National coronavirus data by state was compiled by the <a href=\"https://github.com/nytimes/covid-19-data/blob/master/us-counties.csv\">New York Times</a>.\n\nJohns Hopkins CSSE data begins on January 22 and was used as a starting point to measure the number of positive cases in each country. Spectator was not able to accurately retrieve daily case numbers in China between the <a href=\"https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa2001316\">first four known cases of coronavirus</a> in Wuhan, on Dec. 29 and January 22, 2020. \n\nGovernmental and university administrative actions and announcements were analyzed from official press releases, university websites, and news sources. There may be some discrepancies in dates due to time differences. All data was last updated March 31, 2020.","USE_EYE_NAV":false,"USE_COVER_HED":false,"DOC_URL":"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gh2UqFOC5Xb7TncFoP3zTanYxWlTCgRHD0XMDGrQErw/edit"}}}}